{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"primaryCategory":"Mind & Well-being","subcategory":"Mindfulness","audienceTags":["theme:mindfulness","theme:presence","audience:meditation","audience:morning"],"sortPriority":39,"groupingLevels":["author"],"groupingLabels":["Teacher"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Mindfulness_Wisdom.json","supplementalDataPath":null,"languageCode":"en","displayNameEnglish":"Mindfulness & Presence","script":"Latin","isRTL":false,"transliterationAvailable":false,"contentRating":"general","sourceId":"mindfulnessWisdom","displayName":"Mindfulness & Presence","version":"1.0","language":"English","edition":"Wikiquote Verified & Public Domain","type":"quotes","browseOrder":"sequence","itemCount":600,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true},"data":[{"id":"mindful-000001","text":"Birds' songs express joy, beauty, and purity, and evoke in us vitality and love. So many beings in the universe love us unconditionally. The trees, the water, and the air don't ask anything of us; they just love us. Even though we need this kind of love, we continue to destroy them. By destroying the animals, the air, and the trees, we are destroying ourselves.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000002","text":"If you see someone who is trying to shoot, to destroy, you have to do your best in order to prevent him or her to do so. You must. But you must do it out of your compassion, of your willingness to protect, and not out of anger. That is the key. If you need to use force, you have to use it, but you have to make sure that you act out of compassion and a willingness to protect, not out of anger.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000003","text":"When you understand the roots of anger in yourself and in the other, your mind will enjoy true peace, joy and lightness","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000004","text":"When you feel anger arising, remember to return to your breathing and follow it. The other person may see that you are practicing, and she may even apologize.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000005","text":"Your first love has no beginning or end. Your first love is not your first love, and it is not your last. It is just love. It is one with everything.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000006","text":"The quality of our lifedepends on the qualityof the seedsthat lie deep in our consciousness.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000007","text":"The present momentcontains past and future.The secret of transformation,is in the way we handle this very moment.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000008","text":"Seeds can produce seedsSeeds can produce formations.Formations can produce seeds.Formations can produce formations.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000009","text":"Undoubtedly, even for enlightened men, however determined they may be, it is very difficult to go against the system. The question posed today is what must we do to prevent ourselves from being taken over by the system? Engaging in political or economic conflict does not seem to be the answer.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000010","text":"One included all, and all were contained in one.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000011","text":"The leaf and his body were one. Neither possessed a separate permanent self. Neither could exist independently from the rest of the universe.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000012","text":"Contemplating the bowl, it is possible to see the interdependent elements which give rise to the bowl.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000013","text":"Freedom from suffering is a great happiness.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000014","text":"The Buddha also counseled the monks and nuns to avoid wasting any precious time by engaging in idle conversation, oversleeping, pursuing fame and recognition, chasing after desires, spending time with people of poor character, and being satisfied with only a shallow understanding of the teaching.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000015","text":"The same clouds that Buddha had seen were in the sky. Each serene step brought to life the old path and white clouds of the Buddha. The path of Buddha was beneath his very feet.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000016","text":"Venerable Svasti and the young buffalo boys were rivers that flowed from that source. Wherever the rivers flowed, the Buddha would be there.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000017","text":"If in our daily life we can smile, if we can be peaceful and happy, not only we, but everyone will profit from it. If we really know how to live, what better way to start the day than with a smile? Our smile affirms our awareness and determination to live in peace and joy. The source of a true smile is an awakened mind.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000018","text":"The miracle is not to walk on water. The miracle is to walk on the green earth in the present moment, to appreciate the peace and beauty that are available now.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000019","text":"In order to rally people, governments need enemies. They want us to be afraid, to hate, so we will rally behind them. And if they do not have a real enemy, they will invent one in order to mobilize us.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000020","text":"To think in terms of either pessimism or optimism oversimplifies the truth. The problem is to see reality as it is. A pessimistic attitude can never create the calm and serene smile which blossoms on the lips of Bodhisattvas and all those who obtain the way.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000021","text":"Reality is reality. It transcends every concept. There is no concept which can adequately describe it, not even the concept of interdependence.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000022","text":"Drink your tea slowly and reverently, as if it is the axis on which the whole earth revolves—slowly, evenly, without rushing toward the future. Live the actual moment. Only this actual moment is life.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000023","text":"It's wonderful to be alive and to walk on earth.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000024","text":"You are a miracle, and everything you touch could be a miracle.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000025","text":"If you look deeply into the palm of your hand, you will see your parents and all generations of your ancestors. All of them are alive in this moment. Each is present in your body. You are the continuation of each of these people.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000026","text":"We have more possibilities available in each moment than we realize.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000027","text":"We are committed to respecting the right of others to be different, to choose what to believe and how to decide. We will, however, learn to help others let go of and transform fanaticism and narrowness through loving speech and compassionate dialogue” p. 104","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000028","text":"Chanting from the heart: Buddhist ceremonies and daily practices (2007)","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000029","text":"Going vegetarian may be the most effective way to fight global warming. Buddhist practitioners have practiced vegetarianism over the last 2000 years. We are vegetarian with the intention to nourish our compassion towards the animals. Now we also know that we eat vegetarian in order to protect the earth...","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000030","text":"Love is the capacity to take care, to protect, to nourish. If you are not capable of generating that kind of energy toward yourself — if you are not capable of taking care of yourself, of nourishing yourself, of protecting yourself — it is very difficult to take care of another person.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000031","text":"Life is filled with suffering, but it is also filled with many wonders, such as the blue sky, the sunshine, and the eyes of a baby. To suffer is not enough. We must also be in touch with the wonders of life. They are within us and all around us, everywhere, anytime.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000032","text":"If we are not happy, if we are not peaceful, we can't share peace and happiness with others, even those we love, those who live under the same roof. If we are peaceful, if we are happy, we can smile and blossom like a flower, and everyone in our family, our entire society, will benefit from our peace.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000033","text":"If a child smiles, if an adult smiles, that is very important. If in our daily life we can smile, if we can be peaceful and happy, not only we, but everyone will profit from it. This is the most basic kind of peace work.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000034","text":"From time to time, to remind ourselves to relax, to be peaceful, we may wish to set aside some time for a retreat, a day of mindfulness, when we can walk slowly, smile, drink tea with a friend, enjoy being together as if we are the happiest people on Earth. This is not a retreat, it is a treat.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000035","text":"During walking meditation, during kitchen and garden work, during sitting meditation, all day long, we can practice smiling. At first you may find it difficult to smile, and we have to think about why. Smiling means that we are ourselves, that we have sovereignty over ourselves, that we are not drowned in forgetfulness. This kind of smile can be seen on the faces of Buddhas and bodhisattvas.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000036","text":"I would like to offer one short poem you can recite from time to time, while breathing and smiling:","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000037","text":"If you are a mountain climber or someone who enjoys the countryside, or the green forest, you know that the forests are our lungs outside of our bodies. Yet we have been acting in a way that has allowed two million square miles of forest land to be destroyed by acid rain. We are imprisoned in our small selves, thinking only of the comfortable conditions for this small self, while we destroy our large self.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000038","text":"There is a lot of anger, frustration, and misunderstanding in the peace movement. The peace movement can write very good protest letters, but they are not yet able to write a love letter. We need to learn to write a letter to the Congress or to the president of the United States that they will want to read, and not just throw away. The way you speak, the kind of understanding, the kind of language you use should not turn people off. The president is a person like any of us.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000039","text":"I know of families where children go into a room like that after breakfast, sit down and breathe ten times, in-out-one, in-out-two, in-out-three, ten times, and then they go to school. This is a very beautiful practice. If your child doesn't wish to breathe ten times, how about three times? Beginning the day with being a Buddha is a very nice way to start the day.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000040","text":"If we are a Buddha in the morning and we try to nourish the Buddha throughout the day, we may be able to come home at the end of a day with a smile - the Buddha is still there. When you become agitated, you do not have to do or say anything. Just follow your breathing and walk slowly into that room. The \"room\" for breathing also symbolizes our own inner Buddha Land, so we can enter it whenever we need to, even if we are not at home.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000041","text":"Doing things in this way has a good effect on everyone, teaching by example, not just with words. When your child is agitated, you don't have to say, \"Go to that room!\" You can take his or her hand and walk together into the room for breathing, and sit quietly together. This is the best education for peace. It is really beautiful to begin the day by being a Buddha. Each time we feel ourselves about to leave our Buddha, we can sit and breathe until we return to our true self.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000042","text":"There are three things I can recommend to you: arranging to have a breathing room in your home, a room for meditation; practicing breathing, sitting, for a few minutes every morning at home with your children; and going out for a slow walking meditation with your children before going to sleep, just ten minutes is enough. These things are very important. They can change our civilization.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000043","text":"We should bow deeply before the orchid and the snail and join our palms reverently before the monarch butterfly and the magnolia tree. The feeling of respect for all species will help us recognize the noblest nature in ourselves.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000044","text":"People usually consider walking on water or in thin air a miracle. But I think the real miracle is not to walk either on water or in thin air, but to walk on earth. Every day we are engaged in a miracle which we don't even recognize: a blue sky, white clouds, green leaves, the black, curious eyes of a child—our own two eyes. All is a miracle.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000045","text":"Breath is the bridge which connects life to consciousness, which unites your body to your thoughts. Whenever your mind becomes scattered, use your breath as the means to take hold of your mind again.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000046","text":"To think in terms of either pessimism or optimism oversimplifies the truth. The problem is to see reality as it is.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000047","text":"He has immense presence and both personal and Buddhist authority. If there is a candidate for \"Living Buddha\" on earth today, it is Thich Nhat Hanh.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000048","text":"He oversees several retreat centers in America and Europe where his disciples engage in the practice of a \"New Age\"-style Zen and rituals created by him that do not have any affinity with or any foundation in traditional Vietnamese Buddhist practices.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000049","text":"A great spiritual leader whose influence can help us find a living peace in everything we do. Thich Nhat Hanh's words connect inner peace with the need for peace in the world in a compelling way.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000050","text":"[Thich Nhat Hanh] shows us the connection between personal inner peace and peace on earth.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000051","text":"One of the things he says is that we don't know how to feel peace. We don't understand the joy that is peace. We think that it's boring. And that is an aesthetic and a social perception. He is dealing with many of these same problems we are facing, and I just know he has some answers.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000052","text":"Thich Nhat Hanh is a real poet.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000053","text":"Our actions are our only true belongings, counsels Thich Nhat Hanh.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000054","text":"Thich Nhat Hanh writes with the voice of the Buddha.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000055","text":"May we let the sadness come and teach us how to live. Let it be the mud for the lotus, as Thay [Thich Nhat Hanh] says. Let us sit with it and let it pass through us so that it might be transformed to something like love.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000056","text":"I do not personally know of anyone more worthy of the Nobel Peace Prize than this gentle Buddhist monk from Vietnam. This would be a notably auspicious year for you to bestow your Prize on the Venerable Nhat Hanh. Here is an apostle of peace and non-violence, cruelly separated from his own people while they are oppressed by a vicious war which has grown to threaten the sanity and security of the entire world.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000057","text":"I know Thich Nhat Hanh, and am privileged to call him my friend...","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000058","text":"Thich Nhat Hanh offers a way out of this nightmare, a solution acceptable to rational leaders. He has traveled the world, counseling statesmen, religious leaders, scholars and writers, and enlisting their support. His ideas for peace, if applied, would build a monument to ecumenism, to world brotherhood, to humanity.","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000059","text":"Profile at Parallax.org","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000060","text":"Profile at dharmamemphis.com","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000061","text":"Profile at Seaox.com","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000062","text":"Buddhist Masters and their Organizations","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000063","text":"SpiritSight.com - Excerpts from selected Thich Nhat Hanh books","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000064","text":"Questions and Answers by Thich Nhat Hanh","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000065","text":"ShambhalaSun Magazine (do a search on \"Thich Nhat Hanh\" for a list of previous articles)","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000066","text":"Speaking of Faith (Downloadable Public Radio broadcast about the teachings of Thich Nhat Hanh)","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000067","text":"Plum Village - Thich Nhat Hanh's main monastery and practice center, located about 85 km east of Bordeaux, France","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000068","text":"Deer Park Monastery - located in Escondido, California","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000069","text":"I Am Home - Community of Mindful Living; home of the \"Mindfulness Bell\" magazine with news, articles, and talks by Thich Nhat Hanh and other Order of Interbeing members","author":"Thich Nhat Hanh","source":"Thích Nhất Hạnh","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000070","text":"We all need to be reminded and encouraged to relax with whatever arises and bring whatever we encounter to the path.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000071","text":"Fear is a natural reaction to moving closer to the truth.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000072","text":"Impermanence becomes vivid in the present moment; so do compassion and wonder and courage. And so does fear.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000073","text":"In fact, anyone who stands on the edge of the unknown, fully in the present without reference point, experiences groundlessness.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000074","text":"The trick is to keep exploring and not bail out, even when we find out that something is not what we thought... Nothing is what we thought.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000075","text":"Emptiness is not what we thought. Neither is mindfulness or fear. Compassion—not what we thought. Love. Buddha nature. Courage.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000076","text":"When things fall apart and we’re on the verge of we know not what, the test of each of us is to stay on that brink and not concretize.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000077","text":"The spiritual journey is not about heaven and finally getting to a place that’s really swell. In fact, that way of looking at things is what keeps us miserable.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000078","text":"Thinking that we can find some lasting pleasure and avoid pain is what in Buddhism is called samsara, a hopeless cycle that goes round and round endlessly and causes us to suffer greatly.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000079","text":"The very first noble truth of the Buddha points out that suffering is inevitable for human beings as long as we believe that things last — that they don’t disintegrate, that they can be counted on to satisfy our hunger for security.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000080","text":"From this point of view, the only time we ever know what’s really going on is when the rug’s been pulled out and we can’t find anywhere to land. We use these situations either to wake ourselves up or to put ourselves to sleep.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000081","text":"When anyone asks me how I got involved in Buddhism, I always say it was because I was so angry with my husband... When that marriage fell apart, I tried hard—very, very hard—to go back to some kind of comfort, some kind of security, some kind of familiar resting place... I knew that annihilation of my old dependent, clinging self was the only way to go.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000082","text":"Life is a good teacher and a good friend. Things are always in transition, if we could only realize it.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000083","text":"Every day, at the moment when things get edgy, we can just ask ourselves, “Am I going to practice peace, or am I going to war?”","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000084","text":"Generally speaking, we regard discomfort in any form as bad news. But for practitioners or spiritual warriors — people who have a certain hunger to know what is true — feelings like disappointment, embarrassment, irritation, resentment, anger, jealousy, and fear, instead of being bad news, are actually very clear moments that... teach us to perk up and lean in when we feel we’d rather collapse and back away.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000085","text":"This very moment is the perfect teacher, and, lucky for us, it’s with us wherever we are.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000086","text":"Meditation is an invitation to notice when we reach our limit and to not get carried away by hope and fear.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000087","text":"Through meditation, we’re able to see clearly what’s going on with our thoughts and emotions, and we can also let them go.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000088","text":"The natural quality of mind is clear, awake, alert, and knowing. Free from fixation. By training in being present, we come to know the nature of our mind. So the more you train in being present - being right here - the more you begin to feel like your mind is sharpening up. The mind that can come back to the present is clearer and more refreshed, and it can better weather all the ambiguities, pains, and paradoxes of life.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000089","text":"The principle of nowness is very important to any effort to establish an enlightened society.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000090","text":"Meditation is just gently coming back again and again to what's right here.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000091","text":"But the Buddhist teachings are not only about removing the symptoms of suffering, they’re about actually removing the cause, or the root, of suffering.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000092","text":"When we multitask and split up our mind into a million directions, we are actually creating our own suffering, because these habits strengthen strong emotional reactivity and discursive thought.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000093","text":"We can't control what's going to happen but we can grow in awareness of what is happening.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000094","text":"But there is that feeling. And there’s always another challenge, and that keeps us humble. Life knocks you off your pedestal.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000095","text":"The experience of a sad and tender heart is what gives birth to fearlessness.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000096","text":"Meditation helps you to meet your edge; it’s where you actually come up against it and you start to lose it.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000097","text":"This is a standard meditation instruction that you can embody in the entirety of your life: do not act out and do not repress. See what happens if you don’t do either of those things.","author":"Pema Chödrön","source":"Pema Chödrön","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000098","text":"I bent over backwards to structure it and find ways to speak about it that avoided as much as possible the risk of its being seen as Buddhist, New Age, Eastern mysticism or just plain flaky.","author":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","source":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000099","text":"A good place to start is with yourself. See if you can give yourself gifts that may be true blessings, such as self-acceptance, or some time each day with no purpose. Practice feeling deserving enough to accept these gifts without obligation—to simply receive from yourself, and from the universe.","author":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","source":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000100","text":"If you know anything about Buddhism, you will know that the most important point is to be yourself and not try to become anything that you are not already. Buddhism is fundamentally about being in touch with your own deepest nature and letting it flow out of you unimpeded.","author":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","source":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000101","text":"Such is the power of mindful, selfless generosity. At the deepest level, there is no giver, no gift, and no recipient…only the universe rearranging itself.","author":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","source":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000102","text":"Breathe and let be... Give yourself permission to allow this moment to be exactly as it is, and allow yourself to be exactly as you are.","author":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","source":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000103","text":"It helps to have a focus for your attention, an anchor line to tether you to the present moment and to guide you back when the mind wanders. The breath serves this purpose exceedingly well. It can be a true ally. Bringing awareness to our breathing, we remind ourselves that we are here now, so we might as well be fully awake for whatever is already happening.","author":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","source":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000104","text":"Be a light unto yourself.","author":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","source":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000105","text":"Mindfulness practice means that we commit fully in each moment to be present; inviting ourselves to interface with this moment in full awareness, with the intention to embody as best we can an orientation of calmness, mindfulness, and equanimity right here and right now.","author":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","source":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000106","text":"To let go means to give up coercing, resisting, or struggling, in exchange for something more powerful and wholesome which comes out of allowing things to be as they are without getting caught up in your attraction to or rejection of them, in the intrinsic stickiness of wanting, of liking and disliking.","author":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","source":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000107","text":"The best way to capture moments is to pay attention. This is how we cultivate mindfulness. Mindfulness means being awake. It means knowing what you are doing.","author":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","source":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000108","text":"Jon Kabat-Zinn describes overwhelm as the all-too-common feeling “that our lives are somehow unfolding faster than the human nervous system and psyche are able to manage well.”","author":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","source":"Jon Kabat-Zinn","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000109","text":"Many people live habitually as if the present moment were an obstacle that they need to overcome in order to get to the next moment, and imagine living your whole life like that. Always, this moment is not quite good enough because you need to get to the next one.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000110","text":"I have little use for the past and rarely think about it; however, I would briefly like to tell you how I came to be a spiritual teacher and how this book came into existence. Until my thirtieth year, I lived in a state of almost continuous anxiety interspersed with periods of suicidal depression. It feels now as if I am talking about some past lifetime or somebody else's life. Introduction","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000111","text":"When you listen to a thought, you are aware not only of the thought but also of yourself as the witness of the thought. A new dimension of consciousness has come in. p. 17","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000112","text":"The greater part of human pain is unnecessary. It is self created as long as the unobserved mind runs your life....The pain that you create now is always some form of non acceptance, some form of unconscious resistance to what is. On the level of thought, the resistance is some form of judgment. On the emotional level, it is some form of negativity. p. 25","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000113","text":"Where there is anger, there is always pain underneath. Or when a dark mood comes upon you and you start getting into a negative mind-pattern and thinking how dreadful your life is, your thinking has become aligned with the pain-body, and you have become unconscious and vulnerable to the pain-body's attack. \"Unconscious,\" the way that I use the word here, means to be identified with some mental or emotional pattern. It implies a complete absence of the watcher. p. 29-30","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000114","text":"The good news is that you can free yourself from your mind. This is the only true liberation. You can take the first step right now.... You'll soon realize: there is the voice, and here I am listening to it, watching it. This I am realization, this sense of your own presence, is not a thought. It arises from beyond the mind.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000115","text":"The great Zen master Rinzai, in order to take his students' attention away from time, would often raise his finger and slowly ask: \"What, at this moment, is lacking?\" A powerful question that does not require an answer on the level of the mind. It is designed to take your attention deeply into the Now. A similar question in the Zen tradition is this: \"If not now, when?\" p. 38","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000116","text":"The Now is also central to the teaching of Sufism, the mystical branch of Islam. Sufis have a saying: \"The Sufi is the son of time present.\" And Rumi, the great poet and teacher of Sufism, declares: \"Past and future veil God from our sight; burn up both of them with fire.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000117","text":"Meister Eckhart, the thirteenth-century spiritual teacher, summed it all up beautifully: \"Time is what keeps the light from reaching us. There is no greater obstacle to God than time.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000118","text":"The past cannot survive in your presence. It can only survive in your absence. p. 76","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000119","text":"Because we live in such a mind-dominated culture, most modern art, architecture, music, and literature are devoid of beauty, of inner essence, with very few exceptions.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000120","text":"You are here to enable the divine purpose of the universe to unfold. That is how important you are! p. 91","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000121","text":"The ego … reduces the present to a means to an end.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000122","text":"Pleasure is always derived from something outside you, whereas joy arises from within.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000123","text":"The past gives you an identity and the future holds the promise of salvation. … Both are illusions.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000124","text":"The future is usually imagined as either better or worse than the present. If the imagined future is better, it gives you hope or pleasurable anticipation. If it is worse, it creates anxiety. Both are illusory.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000125","text":"Whereas before you dwelt in time and paid brief visits to the Now, have your dwelling place in the Now and pay brief visits to past and future.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000126","text":"If there is no joy, ease, or lightness in what you are doing, it does not necessarily mean that you need to change what you are doing. It may be sufficient to change the how. “How” is always more important than “what.” See if you can give much more attention to the doing than to the result that you want to achieve through it.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000127","text":"To be free of time is to be free of the psychological need of past for your identity and future for your fulfillment.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000128","text":"Ask yourself what “problem” you have right now, not next year, tomorrow, or five minutes from now. What is wrong with this moment?","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000129","text":"The reason why you don't put your hand in the fire is not because of fear, it's because you know you'll get burned. You don't need fear to avoid an unnecessary danger, just a minimum of intelligence and common sense.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000130","text":"If your destination, or the steps you are going to take in the future, take up so much of your attention that they become more important to you than the step you are taking now, then you completely miss the journey’s inner purpose, which has nothing to do with where you are going or what you are doing, but everything to do with how. It has nothing to do with future but everything to do with the quality of your consciousness at this moment.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000131","text":"Every outer purpose is doomed to “fail” sooner or later, simply because it is subject to the law of impermanence of all things.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000132","text":"A true spiritual teacher does not have anything to teach in the conventional sense of the word, does not have anything to give or add to you, such as new information, beliefs, or rules of conduct. The only function of such a teacher is to help you remove that which separates you from the truth of who you already are and what you already know in the depth of your being.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000133","text":"When you lose touch with inner stillness, you lose touch with yourself. When you lose touch with yourself, you lose yourself in the world. Your innermost sense of self, of who you are, is inseparable from stillness. This is the “I Am” that is deeper than name and form.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000134","text":"Stillness is your essential nature. What is stillness? The inner space or awareness in which the words on this page are being perceived and become thoughts. Without that awareness, there would be no perception, no thoughts, no world. (Ch 1)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000135","text":"You are that awareness, disguised as a person. (Ch 1)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000136","text":"In the Bible, it says that God created the world and saw that it was good. That is what you see when you look from stillness without thought. (Ch 1)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000137","text":"Do you need more knowledge? Is more information going to save the world, or faster computers, more scientific or intellectual analysis? Is it not wisdom that humanity needs most at this time? But what is wisdom and where is it to be found? Wisdom comes with the ability to be still. Just look and just listen. No more is needed. Being still, looking, and listening activates the non-conceptual intelligence within you. Let stillness direct your words and actions. (Ch 1)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000138","text":"There is an aliveness in you that you can feel with your Being, not just in the head. Every cell is alive in that presence in which you don't need to think. Yet, in that state, if thought is required for some practical purpose, it is there. The mind can still operate, and it operated beautifully when the greater intelligence that you are uses it and expresses itself through it. (Ch 2)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000139","text":"Finding that dimension frees you and the world from the suffering you inflict on yourself and others when the mind-made “little me” is all you know and runs your life. Love, joy, creative expansion, and lasting inner peace cannot come into your life except through that unconditioned dimension of consciousness. (Ch 2)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000140","text":"A moment of danger can bring about a temporary cessation of the stream of thinking and thus give you a taste of what it means to be present, alert, aware. (Ch 2)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000141","text":"The Truth is far more all-encompassing than the mind could ever comprehend. No thought can encapsulate the Truth. At best, it can point to it. For example, it can say: “All things are intrinsically one.” That is a pointer, not an explanation. Understanding these words means feeling deep within you the truth to which they point. (Ch 2)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000142","text":"The mind is incessantly looking not only for food for thought; it is looking for food for its identity, its sense of self. This is how the ego comes into existence and continuously re-creates itself.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000143","text":"When you think or speak about yourself, when you say, “I,” what you usually refer to is “me and my story.” This is the “I” of your likes and dislikes, fears and desires, the “I” that is never satisfied for long. It is a mind-made sense of who you are, conditioned by the past and seeking to find its fulfillment in the future.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000144","text":"Can you see that this “I” is fleeting, a temporary formation, like a wave pattern on the surface of the water? Who is it that sees this? Who is it that is aware of the fleetingness of your physical and psychological form? I am. This is the deeper “I” that has nothing to do with past and future.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000145","text":"No self, no problem,” said the Buddhist master when asked to explain the deeper meaning of Buddhism.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000146","text":"Confusion, anger, depression, violence, and conflict arise when humans forget who they are. Yet how easy it is to remember the truth and thus return home: I am not my thoughts, emotions, sense perceptions, and experiences. I am not the content of my life. I am Life. I am the space in which all things happen. I am consciousness. I am the Now. I Am. (Ch 4)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000147","text":"The now is inseparable from who you are at the deepest level.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000148","text":"All the misery on the planet arises due to a personalized sense of me or us. That covers up the essence of who you are. When you are unaware of that inner essence, in the end, you always create misery. It's as simple as that. When you don't know who you are, you create a mind-made self as a substitute for your beautiful, divine being and cling to that fearful and needy self. Protecting and enhancing that false sense of self then becomes your primary motivating force. (Ch 5)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000149","text":"Most people's lives are run by desire and fear. Desire is the need to add something to yourself in order to be yourself more fully. All fear is the fear of losing something, and thereby become diminished and be less. These two movements obscure the fact that being cannot be given or taken away. Being in its fullness is already within you, now. (Ch 5)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000150","text":"By knowing yourself as the awareness in which phenomenal existence happens, you become free of dependency on phenomena and free of self seeking in situations, places, and conditions. In other words, what happens or doesn't happen is not that important anymore. Things lose their heaviness, their seriousness. A playfulness comes into your life. You recognize this world as a cosmic dance, the dance of form. (Ch 5)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000151","text":"Whenever you are able, have a “look” inside yourself to see whether you are unconsciously creating conflict between the inner and the outer, between your external circumstances at that moment–where you are, who you are with, or what you are doing–and your thoughts and feelings. Can you feel how painful it is to internally stand in opposition to what is?","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000152","text":"When you recognize this, you also realize that you are now free to give up this futile conflict, this inner state of war. (Ch 6)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000153","text":"How often each day, if you were to verbalize your inner reality at that moment, would you have to say, “I don't want to be where I am?” What does it feel like when you don't want to be where you are–the traffic jam, your place of work, the airport lounge, the people you are with? (Ch 6)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000154","text":"It is true, of course, that some places are good places to walk out of–and sometimes that may well be the most appropriate thing for you to do. In many cases, however, walking out is not an option. In all those cases, the “I don't want to be here” is not only useless but also dysfunctional. It makes you and others unhappy. (Ch 6)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000155","text":"It has been said: wherever you go, there you are. In other words: you are here. Always. Is it so hard to accept that? (Ch 6)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000156","text":"Do you really need to mentally label every sense perception and experience? Do you really need to have a reactive like/dislike relationship with life where you are in almost continuous conflict with situations and people? Or is that just a deep seated mental habit that can be broken? Not by doing anything, but by allowing this moment to be as it is. (Ch 7)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000157","text":"The habitual and reactive “no” strengthens the ego. “Yes” weakens it. Your form identity, the ego, cannot survive surrender. (Ch 6)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000158","text":"Whatever you accept completely will take you to peace, including the acceptance that you cannot accept, that you are in resistance. (Ch 6)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000159","text":"Leave Life alone. Let it be.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000160","text":"Surrender is surrender to this moment, not to a story through which you interpret this moment and then try to resign yourself to it. … Can you accept the isness of this moment and not confuse it with a story the mind has created around it? (Ch 6)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000161","text":"We depend on nature not only for our physical survival. We also need nature to show us the way home, the way out of the prison of our own minds. We got lost in doing, thinking, remembering, anticipating–lost in a maze of complexity and a world of problems.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000162","text":"We have forgotten what rocks, plants, and animals still know. We have forgotten how to be–to be still, to be ourselves, to be where life is: Here and Now. (Ch 7)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000163","text":"Whenever you bring your attention to anything natural, anything that has come into existence without human intervention, you step out of the prison of conceptualized thinking and, to some extent, participate in the state of connectedness with Being in which everything natural still exists. (Ch 7)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000164","text":"To bring your attention to a stone, a tree, or an animal does not mean to think about it, but simply to perceive it, to hold it in your awareness.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000165","text":"Something of its essence then transmits itself to you. You can sense how still it is, and in doing so the same stillness arises within you. You sense how deeply it rests in Being–completely at one with what it is and where it is. In realizing this, you too come to a place of rest deep within yourself. (Ch 7)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000166","text":"How quick we are to form an opinion of a person, to come to a conclusion about them. It is satisfying to the egoic mind to label another human being, to give them a conceptual identity, to pronounce righteous judgment upon them.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000167","text":"How wonderful to go beyond wanting and fearing in your relationships. Love does not want or fear anything. (Ch 8)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000168","text":"If her past were your past, her pain your pain, her level of consciousness your level of consciousness, you would think and act exactly as she does. With this realization comes forgiveness, compassion, peace. (Ch 8)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000169","text":"The ego doesn’t like to hear this, because if it cannot be reactive and righteous anymore, it will lose strength. (Ch 8)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000170","text":"...the ego's need to be periodically in conflict with something or someone in order to strengthen its sense of separation between me and the other, without which it cannot survive. (Ch 8)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000171","text":"Whenever you meet anyone, no matter how briefly, do you acknowledge their being by giving them your full attention, or are you reducing them to a means to an end, a mere function or role. What is the quality of your relationship with the cashier at the supermarket, the parking attendant, the repair man, the customer? (Ch 8)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000172","text":"When you walk though a forest that has not been tamed and interfered with by man, you will see not only abundant life around you, but you will also encounter fallen trees and decaying trunks, rotting leaves and decomposing matter at every step. (Ch 9)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000173","text":"Wherever you look, you will find death as well as life. Upon closer scrutiny, however, you will discover that the decomposing tree trunk and rotting leaves not only give birth to new life, but are full of life themselves. (Ch 9)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000174","text":"Microorganisms are at work. Molecules are rearranging themselves. So death isn’t to be found anywhere. There is only the metamorphosis of life forms. What can you learn from this? (Ch 9)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000175","text":"Death is not the opposite of life. Life has no opposite. The opposite of death is birth. Life is eternal.(Ch 9)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000176","text":"The interconnectedness of all things: Buddhists have always known it and physicists now confirm it. Nothing that happens is an isolated event, it only appears to be. The more we judge and label it, the more we isolate it.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000177","text":"The wholeness of life becomes fragmented through our thinking. Yet the totality of life has brought this event about. It is part of the web of interconnectedness that is the cosmos. This means whatever is could not be otherwise. (Ch 10)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000178","text":"In most cases, we cannot begin to understand what role a seemingly senseless event may have within the totality of the cosmos but recognizing its inevitability within the vastness of the whole can be the beginning of an inner acceptance of what is and thus a realignment with the wholeness of life. (Ch 10)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000179","text":"The inspiration for the title of this book came from a Bible prophecy that seems more applicable now than at any other time in human history. It occurs in both the Old and the New Testament and speaks of the collapse of the existing world order and the arising of “a new heaven and a new earth.\" We need to understand here that heaven is not a location but refers to the inner realm of consciousness. This is the esoteric meaning of the word, and this is also its meaning in the teachings of Jesus.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000180","text":"Collective human consciousness and life on our planet are intrinsically connected. “A new heaven” is the emergence of a transformed state of human consciousness, and “a new earth” is its reflection in the physical realm.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000181","text":"The greatest achievement of humanity is not its works of art, science, or technology, but the recognition of its own dysfunction, its own madness.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000182","text":"In the distant past, this recognition already came to a few individuals. A man called Gautama Siddhartha, who lived 2,600 years ago in India, was perhaps the first who saw it with absolute clarity. Later the title Buddha was conferred upon him. Buddha means “the awakened one.”","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000183","text":"Another of humanity’s early awakened teachers emerged in China. His name was Lao Tzu. He left a record of his teaching in the form of one of the most profound spiritual books ever written, the Tao Te Ching.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000184","text":"To recognize one’s own insanity, is of course, the arising of sanity, the beginning of healing and transcendence.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000185","text":"The possibility of such a transformation has been the central message of the great wisdom teachings of humankind. The messengers—Buddha, Jesus, and others, not all of them known—were humanity's early flowers. They were precursors, rare and precious beings. A widespread flowering was not yet possible at that time, and their message became largely misunderstood and often greatly distorted. It certainly did not transform human behavior, except in a small minority of people.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000186","text":"This book itself is a transformational device that has come out of the arising new consciousness. The ideas and concepts presented here may be important, but they are secondary. They are no more than signposts pointing toward awakening. As you read, a shift takes place within you.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000187","text":"What a liberation to realize that the \"voice in my head\" is not who I am. Who am I then? The one who sees that.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000188","text":"Only by awakening can you know the true meaning of that word.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000189","text":"When you don't cover up the world with words and labels, a sense of the miraculous returns to your life.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000190","text":"How do you let go of attachment to things? Don't even try. It's impossible. Attachment to things drops away by itself when you no longer seek to find yourself in them.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000191","text":"Accepting means you allow yourself to feel whatever it is you are feeling at that moment...you can't argue with what is. Well, you can, but if you do, you suffer.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000192","text":"The more unconscious individuals, groups, or nations are, the more likely it is that egoic pathology will assume the form of physical violence. Violence is a primitive but still very widespread way in which the ego attempts to assert itself, to prove itself right or another wrong. With very unconscious people, arguments can easily lead to physical violence.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000193","text":"Awareness is the greatest agent for change.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000194","text":"You do not become good by trying to be good, but by finding the goodness that is already within you, and allowing that goodness to emerge.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000195","text":"Instead of asking \"what do I want from life?\", a more powerful question is, \"what does life want from me?","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000196","text":"Don't seek happiness. If you seek it, you won't find it, because seeking is the antithesis of happiness.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000197","text":"Nothing ever happened in the past that can prevent you from being present now; and if the past cannot prevent you from being present now, what power does it have?","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000198","text":"All the things that truly matter - beauty, love, creativity, joy, inner peace - arise from beyond the mind.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000199","text":"You cannot find yourself in the past or future. The only place where you can find yourself is in the Now.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000200","text":"When you lose touch with inner stillness, you lose touch with yourself.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000201","text":"Suffering has a noble purpose: the evolution of the consciousness and the burning up of the ego.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000202","text":"Being must be felt. It can't be thought.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000203","text":"Listen to people's stories and they all could be entitled \"Why I Cannot Be At Peace Now\" The ego doesn't know that your only opportunity for being at peace is now.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000204","text":"Presence is a state of inner spaciousness.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000205","text":"Nonresistance is the key to the greatest power in the universe.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000206","text":"Being spiritual has nothing to do with what you believe and everything to do with your state of consciousness.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000207","text":"When you lose touch with inner stillness, you lose touch with yourself. When you lose touch with yourself, you lose yourself in the world.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000208","text":"The human condition: lost in thought.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000209","text":"Life is the dancer and you are the dance.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000210","text":"What you react to in others, you strengthen in yourself.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000211","text":"We could say that the totality, life wants the sapling to become a tree, but the sapling doesn't see itself as separate from life and so wants nothing for itself. It is one with what life wants. That's why it isn't worried or stressed. And, if it has to die prematurely, it dies with ease.....","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000212","text":"When you accept everything for what it is without labels you are outside of your ego.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000213","text":"Right now we are being given the experience we need to raise our consciousness.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000214","text":"A new species is arising on the planet. It is arising now, and you are it!","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000215","text":"The primary cause of unhappiness is never the situation but your thoughts about it. Be aware of the thoughts you are thinking. Separate them from the situation, which is always neutral. There is the situation or the fact, and here are my thoughts about it. Life isn't as serious as the mind makes it out to be.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000216","text":"Try to catch the voice in your head, in the very moment it complains about something. Recognise it for what it is: the voice of the ego, no more than a thought.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000217","text":"People believe themselves to be dependent on what happens to them for their happiness. They don't realize that what happens is the most unstable thing in the universe. It changes constantly. They look upon the present moment as either marred by something that has happened and shouldn't have or as deficient because of something that has not happened but should have.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000218","text":"The more shared past there is in a relationship, the more present you need to be; otherwise, you will be forced to relive the past again and again.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000219","text":"You do not become good by trying to be good, but by finding the goodness that is already within you and allowing that goodness to emerge. If peace is really what you want, then choose peace. The moment that judgement stops through acceptance of what it is, you are free of the mind. You have made room for love, for joy, for peace.","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000220","text":"The Ageless Wisdom Teachings","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000221","text":"The Reappearance of the Christ, by Alice A Bailey","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000222","text":"The Celestine Prophecy","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000223","text":"Maitreya (Theosophy)","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000224","text":"The Aquarian Conspiracy, by Marilyn Ferguson","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000225","text":"A New Earth, by Eckhart Tolle","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000226","text":"The Power of Now, by Eckhart Tolle","author":"Eckhart Tolle","source":"Eckhart Tolle","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000227","text":"What is true zazen? What do you mean by Zen becomes Zen and you become you? You become you is a very important point. You become you. When you become you, even though you are in bed, you may not be you most of the time. Even though you are sitting here, I wonder whether you are you in its true sense. So to be you is zazen.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000228","text":"So it is not a matter of whether it is possible to attain Buddhahood, or if it is possible to make a tile a jewel. But just to work, just to live in this world with this understanding is the most important point, and that is our practice. That is true zazen.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000229","text":"The highest truth is daiji, translated as dai jiki in Chinese scriptures. This is the subject of the question the emperor asked Bodhidharma: \"What is the First Principle?\" Bodhidharma said, \"I don't know.\" \"I don't know\" is the First Principle.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000230","text":"Communication is — start by understanding — your own understanding about people. Even though you want them to understand you, you know, it is — unless you understand people, it is almost impossible. Don't you think so? Only when you understand people, they may understand you. So even though you do not say anything, if you understand people there is some communication.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000231","text":"When you do something, you should burn yourself completely, like a good bonfire, leaving no trace of yourself.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000232","text":"There are, strictly speaking, no enlightened people, there is only enlightened activity.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000233","text":"In the beginner's mind there are many possibilities, in the expert's there are few.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000234","text":"The true purpose of Zen is to see things as they are, to observe things as they are, and to let everything go as it goes. Zen practice is to open up our small mind.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000235","text":"You should rather be grateful for the weeds you have in your mind, because eventually they will enrich your practice.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000236","text":"Zazen practice is the direct expression of our true nature. Strictly speaking, for a human being, there is no other practice than this practice; there is no other way of life than this way of life.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000237","text":"If you take pride in your attainment or become discouraged because of your idealistic effort, your practice will confine you by a thick wall.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000238","text":"The purpose of studying Buddhism is not to study Buddhism but to study ourselves. You are not your body. You are the Big Activity. You are just expressing the smallest particle of the Big Activity. That is all. But when you become attached to a temporal expression of the Big Activity, it is time to talk about Buddhism.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000239","text":"The basic teaching of Buddhism is the teaching of transiency or change. That everything changes is the basic truth for each existence. No one can deny this truth and all teaching of Buddhism is condensed within it. This is the teaching for all of us. Wherever we go this teaching is true. This teaching is also understood as the teaching of selflessness. Because each existence is in constant change, there is no abiding self.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000240","text":"When we do not expect anything we can be ourselves. That is our way, to live fully in each moment of time.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000241","text":"It is a big mistake to think that the best way to express yourself is to do whatever you want, acting as you please. This is not expressing yourself. If you know what to do exactly, and you do it, then you can express yourself fully.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000242","text":"All descriptions of reality are limited expressions of the world of emptiness. Yet we attach to the descriptions and think they are reality. That is a mistake.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000243","text":"Instead of respecting things, we want to use them for ourselves and if it is difficult to use them, we want to conquer them.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000244","text":"Real Freedom is to not feel limited when wearing this Zen robe, this troublesome formal robe. Similarly, in our busy life we should wear this civilization without being bothered by it, without ignoring it, without being caught by it.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000245","text":"Nothing we see or hear is perfect. But right there in the imperfection is perfect reality.","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000246","text":"Crooked Cucumber: The Life and Teaching of Shunryu Suzuki","author":"Shunryu Suzuki","source":"Shunryu Suzuki","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000247","text":"He whose intellect overcomes his desire is higher than the angels; he whose desire overcomes his intellect is less than an animal.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000248","text":"The fault is in the one who blames. Spirit sees nothing to criticize.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000249","text":"This discipline and rough treatment are a furnace to extract the silver from the dross. This testing purifies the gold by boiling the scum away.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000250","text":"Fortunate is he who does not carry envy as a companion.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000251","text":"The idol of your self is the mother of all idols. To regard the self as easy to subdue is a mistake.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000252","text":"If you wish mercy, show mercy to the weak.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000253","text":"If you dig a pit for others to fall into, you will fall into it yourself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000254","text":"Many of the faults you see in others, dear reader, are your own nature reflected in them.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000255","text":"The lion who breaks the enemy's ranks is a minor hero compared to the lion who overcomes himself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000256","text":"Whoever gives reverence receives reverence.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000257","text":"Were there no men of vision, all who are blind would be dead.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000258","text":"If you are wholly perplexed and in straits, have patience, for patience is the key to joy.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000259","text":"If you are irritated by every rub, how will your mirror be polished?","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000260","text":"Anyone in whom the troublemaking self has died, sun and cloud obey. As his heart is afire with knowledge and love, the sun cannot burn him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000261","text":"If you wish to shine like day, burn up the night of self-existence. Dissolve in the Being who is everything.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000262","text":"There is no worse sickness for the soul, O you who are proud, than this pretense of perfection. The heart and eyes must bleed a lot before self-complacency falls away.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000263","text":"God turns you from one feeling to another and teaches by means of opposites, so that you will have two wings to fly, not one.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000264","text":"When the remedy you have offered only increases the disease, then leave him who will not be cured, and tell your story to someone who seeks the truth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000265","text":"Whoever enters the Way without a guide will take a hundred years to travel a two-day journey.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000266","text":"Whoever undertakes a profession without a master becomes the laughingstock of city and town.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000267","text":"Even though you're not equipped,keep searching:equipment isn't necessary on the way to the Lord.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000268","text":"If an ant seeks the rank of Solomon,don't smile contemptuously upon its quest.Everything you possess of skill, and wealth and handicraft,wasn't it first merely a thought and a quest?","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000269","text":"Come, seek, for search is the foundation of fortune:Every success depends upon focusing the heart.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000270","text":"That which God said to the rose,and caused it to laugh in full-blown beauty,He said to my heart,and made it a hundred times more beautiful.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000271","text":"Many have been led astray by the Qur'an:by clinging to that rope many have fallen into the well.There is no fault in the rope, O perverse man,for it was you who had no desire to reach the top.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000272","text":"The eye of outward sense is as the palm of a hand, The whole of the object is not grasped in the palm. The sea itself is one thing, the foam another; Neglect the foam, and regard the sea with your eyes.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000273","text":"When you see anyone complainingof such and such a person's ill-nature and bad temper,know that the complainant is bad-tempered,forasmuch as he speaks ill of that bad-tempered person,because he alone is good-tempered who is quietly forbearingtowards the bad-tempered and ill-natured.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000274","text":"Everyone sees the unseen in proportion to the clarity of his heart, and that depends upon how much he has polished it. Whoever has polished it more sees more — more unseen forms become manifest to him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000275","text":"Love is the ark appointed for the righteous,Which annuls the danger and provides a way of escape.Sell your cleverness and buy bewilderment.Cleverness is mere opinion, bewilderment intuition.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000276","text":"Reason is like an officer when the King appears;The officer then loses his power and hides himself.Reason is the shadow cast by God; God is the sun.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000277","text":"How can these works and this earning in the way of righteousness be accomplished without a master, O father? Can you practice the meanest profession in the world without a master's guidance?","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000278","text":"Are you fleeing from Love because of a single humiliation?What do you know of Love except the name?Love has a hundred forms of pride and disdain,and is gained by a hundred means of persuasion.Since Love is loyal, it purchases one who is loyal:it has no interest in a disloyal companion.The human being resembles a tree; its root is a covenant with God:that root must be cherished with all one's might.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000279","text":"If in thirst you drink water from a cup, you see God in it. Those who are not in love with God will see only their own faces in it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000280","text":"The lower self does not want anyone to receive anything from anybody else, and if it is aware of something receiving a special boon, it seeks to destroy it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000281","text":"Whatever possessions and objects of its desires the lower self may obtain, it hangs on to them, refusing to let them go out of greed for more, or out of fear of poverty and need.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000282","text":"I died as a mineral and became a plant,I died as plant and rose to animal,I died as animal and I was Man.Why should I fear? When was I less by dying?Yet once more I shall die as Man, to soarWith angels blest; but even from angelhoodI must pass on: all except God doth perish.When I have sacrificed my angel-soul,I shall become what no mind e'er conceived.Oh, let me not exist! for Non-existenceProclaims in organ tones, 'To Him we shall return.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000283","text":"The branch might seem like the fruit's origin:In fact, the branch exists because of the fruit.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000284","text":"There's no courage\", The Prophet said, \"before the war has begun.\"Drunkards vaunt their bravery when you speak of war.But in the blaze of battle they scatter like mice.I'm astonished by the man who wants purityAnd yet trembles when the harshness of polishing begin...When a man beats a carpet again and againIt's not the carpet he's attacking, but the dirt in it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000285","text":"Love is the path and road of our ProphetWe were born from Love and Love was our mother.O you who are our mother, you are hidden within veils,Concealed from our disbelieving natures","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000286","text":"The fire of Love cooks meEvery night it drags me to the Tavern.It seats me with the People of the TavernSo that no one except the People of the Tavern will know me.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000287","text":"By eating meagerly, you become clever and aware.And by eating gluttonously, you become foolish and idle.Your being full of misery is entirely from your gluttony.You will become less miserable if you become a sparse eater.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000288","text":"If you dwell with unaware people, you will be cold,But if you dwell with aware ones, you will be a true manGo, and build your hermit cell inside a furnace, like goldIf you go out of the furnace, you will be frozen solid","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000289","text":"Dwell in the place where your companions are spiritual heroes,So that they may wash the foul soot from your [heart]Don't think about their faults, for theyWill know about it before you think.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000290","text":"I am so happy, I cannot be contained in the world;But like a spirit, I am hidden from the eyes of the world.If the foot of the trees were not tied to earth, they would be pursuing me;For I have blossomed so much, I am the envy of the gardens.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000291","text":"Study me as much as you like, you will not know me, &nbsp;&nbsp; for I differ in a hundred ways from what you see me to be. Put yourself behind my eyes and see me as I see myself, &nbsp;&nbsp; for I have chosen to dwell in a place you cannot see.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000292","text":"We have a way from this visible world to the Unseen, for we are the companions of religion's messenger.We have a way from the house to the garden, we are the neighbor of the cypress and jasmine.Every day we come to the garden and see a hundred blossoms.In order to scatter them among the lovers, we will our robes to overflowing...Behold our words! They are the fragrance of those roses--we are the rosebush of certainty's rosegarden.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000293","text":"Our caravan leader is the pride of the world, Mustafa [Muhammad].","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000294","text":"Everyone has been made for some particular work, and the desire for that work has been put in every heart.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000295","text":"The men of God are like fishes in the ocean; they pop up into view on the surface here and there and everywhere, as they please.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000296","text":"Let the beauty of what you love be what you do.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000297","text":"I want a heart which is split, part by part, because of the pain of separation from God, so that I might explain my longing and complaint to it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000298","text":"The Sufi is hanging on to Muhammad, like Abu Bakr.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000299","text":"I am the servant of the Qur'an as long as I have life.I am the dust on the path of [Muhammad], the Chosen one.If anyone quotes anything except this from my sayings,I am quit of him and outraged by these words","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000300","text":"You were born with wings. Why prefer to crawl through life?","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000301","text":"Wherever you stand, be the soul of that place.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000302","text":"Seek truth from thought, not in mouldy books. Look in the sky to find the moon, not in the pool.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000303","text":"Ah, me! so poor, can I declare that friend, who never had another friend his like,—none, therefore, who could know his soul?","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000304","text":"Supreme Being soars above thought and imagination. We are lost when we would comprehend or even suspect that which he is. How vain, then, to seek words worthy of that Being! Let it suffice us to adore in reverent silence!","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000305","text":"Thou, nearer to me than I to myself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000306","text":"O heart! weak follower of the weak,&nbsp;&nbsp;That thou shouldst traverse land and sea, In this far place that God to seek&nbsp;&nbsp;Who long ago had come to thee!","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000307","text":"The prophets hear in their mind voices that others never perceive, as the voices of the Peris, which, although they sound out clearly, are never apprehended by our ears.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000308","text":"This universe is a drop from the ocean of his beauty, unable from its fulness to find place in the parent bosom.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000309","text":"When rises the sun and chases the night,What need have we then of the lamp for a light?When the friend all beloved appears to the eye,What want dost thou feel that the post bring him nigh?But when the rose-time is past, and the rose-bloom gone by,Then gladly the eye seeks the water of roses to spy.Is the Master within to thy soul not revealed?Well then may’st thou turn to the Volume of message unsealed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000310","text":"As water from the glasses is all poured into one vessel, so all the praises are mingled together. Since He that is celebrated is wholly one, all religions form but one religion.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000311","text":"The compass only serves to direct the prayers of those who are outside of the Caaba, whilst within it no one knows the use of it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000312","text":"If this world were our abiding place, we might complain that it makes our bed so hard: But it is only our night-quarters on a journey; and who can expect home comforts?","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000313","text":"As the stranger, far distant in foreign climes, draws towards home, so the soul, from midst of this world of multiplicity, pants and soars upward to the Unity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000314","text":"Rabia, sick upon her bed,By two saints was visited,Holy Malik, Hassan wise,—Men of mark in Moslem eyes.Hassan says, \"Whose prayer is pureWill God's chastisements endure.\"Malik, from a deeper sense,Uttered his experience:\"He who hears his Master's voiceWill in chastisement rejoice.\"Rabia saw some selfish willIn their maxims lingering still,And replied, \"O men of grace!He who sees his Master's face,Will not in his prayer recallThat he is chastised at all.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000315","text":"Love is the water of life; receive it in thy heart and soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000316","text":"None but the sun can display the sun.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000317","text":"Pants thy spirit to be giftedWith a deathless life,Let it seek to be upliftedO’er earth’s storm and strife.Spurn its joys,—its ties dissever,Hopes and fears divest;Thus, aspire to live for ever,Be for ever blest.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000318","text":"Tis marvellous by what way thou wentest from the worldThou didst strongly shake thy wings and feathers and having broken thy cageDidst ae to the air and journey towards the world of soul.Thou wert a favourite falcon kept in captivity by an old womanWhen thou heard’st the falcon-drum, thou didst fly away into the void.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000319","text":"After all soul is linked to bodyThough it in nowise resembles the bodyThe power of the light of the eye is mated with fatThe light of the heart is hidden in a drop of bloodJoy harbours in the kidneys and pain in the liverThe lamp of reason in the brains of the head.These connections are not without a why and howBut reason is at a loss to understand the how.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000320","text":"For this cause, O son, the Prince of men declared'The majority of those in Paradise are the foolish'.Cleverness is as a wind raising storms of prideBe foolish, so that your heart may he at peace.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000321","text":"This world of illusions, fancies, desires and fearsIs a mighty obstacle in the traveller's path.Thus when these forms of delusive imaginationsMisled Abraham, who was a very mountain of wisdom.He said of the star 'This is my Lord'.Having fallen into the midst of the world of illusionSeeing then that this world of eye-fascinating illusionSeduced from the right path such a mountain as Abraham.So that he said of the star 'This is my Lord',What will not its illusions effect on a stupid ass?","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000322","text":"First he appeared in the class of inorganic things,Next he passed therefrom into that of plants,For years he lived as one of the plants,Remembering naught of his inorganic state so different,And when he passed from the vegetive to the animal stateHe had no remembrance of his state as a plant.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000323","text":"The prophets chose the better part, futurity.The foolish chose the worst, the world's fatuity.Each bird will flock with birds of its own feather stillThe cock well knows his mate and follows where she will.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000324","text":"The lover is a monarch; two worlds lie at his feet;The king pays no heed to what lies at his feet;'Tis love and the lover that live to all eternitySet not thy heart on aught else; 'tis only borrowed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000325","text":"The root of hatred is hell and that hate of yoursIs a part of that whole and is the foe of your religionSince you are a part of hell, beware!For the part ever tends towards its wholeBut if you are a portion of heaven, O renowned one,Your joy will be as lasting as heaven itself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000326","text":"Let us seek refuge with Allah from Satan;Alas! we are perishing from his insolence.The dog is one yet he enters a thousand forms;Whatever he enters, straight becomes himself;Whatever makes you shiver, know he is in it,The Devil is hidden beneath its outward form.When he finds no form at hand, he enters your thoughtsTo cause them to draw you into sin.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000327","text":"For love of our Almighty God, the Lord of all,Who would not die; a stock, a block, we needs must call.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000328","text":"Imitate the water-wheel that groans and weeps;By prayers and groans and tears a man his heart pure keeps;Wouldst thou shed tears? Feel pity when thou meetest woe,Wouldst mercy find? Show mercy, when men bow them low.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000329","text":"Our celestial spirit is free to eternity,Although for a short time we are imprisoned in forms of flesh.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000330","text":"With thee hell would he a mansion of delightWith thee a prison would be a rose garden.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000331","text":"With thee how should we be afraid of lossO thou, who turnest every loss to gain.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000332","text":"Why, when God’s earth is so wide, have you fallen asleep in prison?","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000333","text":"The majority of those in Paradise are the simpleWho have escaped the snares of philosophy.Strip yourself bare of overweening intellectThat grace may ever be shed upon you from above.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000334","text":"Whereas want of fidelity is shameful even in dogs,How can it be right in men?God Almighty himself makes boast of fidelitySaying 'Who is more faithful to his promise than we?","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000335","text":"Open your arms if you desire an embrace,Break the idol of clay that you may behold the face of the fair.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000336","text":"Earth receives the seed and guards it,&nbsp;&nbsp;Trustfully it dies:Then what teeming life rewards it,&nbsp;&nbsp;For self-sacrifice.With green leaf and clustering blossom&nbsp;&nbsp;Clad, or golden fruit,See it from earth’s cheerless bosom &nbsp;&nbsp;Ever sunward shoot.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000337","text":"Hearken to the reed-flute, how it discoursesWhen complaining of the pains of separation;'Ever since they tore me from my osier-bed,My plaintive notes have moved men and women to tears.I burst my breast striving to give vent to sighs,And to express the pangs of yearning for my home;He who abides far away from his home,Is ever longing for the day he shall return.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000338","text":"Come, come for you will not find another friend like Me,Where indeed is a Beloved like Me in all the world?Come, come, and do not spend your life in wandering to and fro,Since there is no market elsewhere for your money.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000339","text":"Come, and think of Me, Who gave you the faculty of thought,Since from my mine you may purchase an ass-load of rubies;Come, advance towards Him Who gave you a foot,Look with all your eyes upon Him Who gave you an eye.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000340","text":"That spiritual garden accompanies them everywhereYet it is never revealed to the eyes of the people,Its fruits ever asking to be gathered,Its fount of life welling up to be drunk.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000341","text":"We used to be on the earth, ignorant of the earth,Ignorant of the treasure buried within it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000342","text":"Thou wert a love-lorn nightingale among owls,The scent of the rose-garden reached thee, and thou didst go to the rose-garden.Thou didst suffer sore headache from this bitter ferment,At last thou wentest to the tavern of eternity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000343","text":"Tis slave-caressing thy love has practised,Else, where is the heart worthy of that love?Every heart that has slept one night in thine airIs like radiant day; thereby the air is illuminated.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000344","text":"How many letters thou writest with Thy Almighty penThrough marvelling thereat stones become as wax;These letters exercise and perplex reason,Write on, O skilful Fair-writer,Imprinting every moment on Not-being the fair formsOf the world of ideals to confound all thought.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000345","text":"Mine eye is from that source, and from another universeHere a world and there a world: I am seated on the threshold;On the threshold are they alone, whose eloquence is mute,'Tis enough to utter this intimation: say no more, draw back thy tongue.","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000346","text":"What pearl art thou that none possesseth the price of thee?What does the world possess that is not thy gift?","author":"Rumi","source":"Rumi","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000347","text":"Let us disperse from our aloofness and serve the weak who made us strong, and cleanse the country in which we live. Let us teach this miserable nation to smile and rejoice with heaven's bounty and glory of life and freedom.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000348","text":"The creator gives no heed to the critic unless he becomes a barren inventor.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000349","text":"My enemy said to me, \"Love your enemy.\" And I obeyed him and loved myself.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000350","text":"Progress lies not in enhancing what is, but in advancing toward what will be.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000351","text":"The tears that you spill, the sorrowful, are sweeter than the laughter of snobs and the guffaws of scoffers.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000352","text":"Man struggles to find life outside himself, unaware that the life he is seeking is within him.”","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000353","text":"To understand the heart and mind of a person, look not at what he has already achieved, but what he aspires to.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000354","text":"My friend, I am not what I seem. Seeming is but a garment I wear — a care-woven garment that protects me from thy questionings and thee from my negligence. The \"I\" in me, my friend, dwells in the house of silence, and therein it shall remain for ever more, unperceived, unapproachable. I would not have thee believe in what I say nor trust in what I do — for my words are naught but thy own thoughts in sound and my deeds thy own hopes in action.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000355","text":"I know faces, because I look through the fabric my own eye weaves, and behold the reality beneath.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000356","text":"I go — as others already crucified have gone. And think not we are weary of crucifixion. For we must be crucified by larger and yet larger men, between greater earths and greater heavens.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000357","text":"O love, whose lordly hand Has bridled my desires,And raised my hunger and my thirst To dignity and pride, Let not the strong in me and the constant Eat the bread or drink the wine That tempt my weaker self. Let me rather starve,And let my heart parch with thirst, And let me die and perish, Ere I stretch my hand To a cup you did not fill, Or a bowl you did not bless.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000358","text":"Love gives naught but itself and takes naught but from itself. Love possesses not nor would it be possessed; For love is sufficient unto love.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000359","text":"Say not, \"I have found the path of the soul.\" Say rather, \"I have found the soul walking upon my path.\" For the soul walks upon all paths. The soul walks not upon a line, neither does it grow like a reed. The soul unfolds itself, like a lotus of countless petals.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000360","text":"Your pain is the breaking of the shell that encloses your understanding. Even as the stone of the fruit must break, that its heart may stand in the sun, so must you know pain.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000361","text":"Love knows not its own depth until the hour of separation.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000362","text":"For in truth it is life that gives unto life-while you, who deem yourself a giver, are but a witness.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000363","text":"Half of what I say is meaningless, but I say it so that the other half may reach you.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000364","text":"A sense of humour is a sense of proportion.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000365","text":"The reality of the other person is not in what he reveals to you, but in what he cannot reveal to you. Therefore, if you would understand him, listen not to what he says but rather to what he does not say.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000366","text":"My loneliness was born when men praised my talkative faults and blamed my silent virtues.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000367","text":"When Life does not find a singer to sing her heart she produces a philosopher to speak her mind.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000368","text":"A truth is to be known always, to be uttered sometimes.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000369","text":"If you sing of beauty though alone in the heart of the desert you will have an audience.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000370","text":"Solitude is a silent storm that breaks down all our dead branches; Yet it sends our living roots deeper into the living heart of the living earth.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000371","text":"Strange that creatures without backbones have the hardest shells.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000372","text":"Friendship is always a sweet responsibility, never an opportunity.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000373","text":"There must be something strangely sacred about salt. It is in our tears and in the sea","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000374","text":"I would be the least among men with dreams and the desire to fulfill them, rather than the greatest with no dreams and no desires.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000375","text":"My face and your faces shall not be masked; our hand shall hold neither sword nor sceptre, and our subjects shall love us in peace and shall not be in fear of us.\" Thus spoke Jesus, and unto all the kingdoms of the earth I was blinded, and unto all the cities of walls and towers; and it was in my heart to follow the Master to His kingdom.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000376","text":"I was dead. I was a woman who had divorced her soul. I was living apart from this self which you now see. I belonged to all men, and to none. They called me harlot, and a woman possessed of seven devils. I was cursed, and I was envied. But when His dawn-eyes looked into my eyes all the stars of my night faded away, and I became Miriam, only Miriam, a woman lost to the earth she had known, and finding herself in new places.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000377","text":"He knew the depth of beauty, He was for ever surprised by its peace and its majesty; and He stood before the earth as the first man had stood before the first day. We whose senses have been dulled, we gaze in full daylight and yet we do not see. We would cup our ears, but we do not hear; and stretch forth our hands, but we do not touch. And though all the incense of Arabia is burned, we go our way and do not smell.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000378","text":"In truth we gaze but do not see, and hearken but do not hear; we eat and drink but do not taste. And there lies the difference between Jesus of Nazareth and ourselves. His senses were all continually made new, and the world to Him was always a new world.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000379","text":"Do you not remember me, Nicodemus, who believed in naught but the laws and decrees and was in continual subjection to observances? And behold me now, a man who walks with life and laughs with the sun from the first moment it smiles upon the mountain until it yields itself to bed behind the hills.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000380","text":"He was gentle, like a man mindful of his own strength. In my dreams I beheld the kings of the earth standing in awe in His presence.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000381","text":"I have pondered long, and I know now that only the pure of heart forgive the thirst that leads to dead waters. And only the sure of foot can give a hand to him who stumbles.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000382","text":"Jesus loved me and I knew not why. And I loved Him because He quickened my spirit to heights beyond my stature, and to depths beyond my sounding. Love is a sacred mystery. To those who love, it remains forever wordless; But to those who do not love, it may be but a heartless jest.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000383","text":"Love is a gracious host to his guests though to the unbidden his house is a mirage and a mockery. Now you would have me explain the miracles of Jesus. We are all the miraculous gesture of the moment; our Lord and Master was the centre of that moment. Yet it was not in His desire that His gestures be known.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000384","text":"I would tell you more of Him, but how shall I? When love becomes vast love becomes wordless. And when memory is overladen it seeks the silent deep.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000385","text":"In a dream I saw Jesus and My God Pan sitting together in the heart of the forest. They laughed at each other's speech, with the brook that ran near them, and the laughter of Jesus was the merrier. And they conversed long.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000386","text":"Once again I say that with death Jesus conquered death, and rose from the grave a spirit and a power. And He walked in our solitude and visited the gardens of our passion. He lies not there in that cleft rock behind the stone. We who love Him beheld Him with these our eyes which He made to see; and we touched Him with these our hands which He taught to reach forth.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000387","text":"You hate Jesus because someone from the North Country said He was the Son of God. But you hate one another because each of you deems himself too great to be the brother of the next man.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000388","text":"You know not that the earth was given in marriage to the sun, and that earth it is who sends us forth to the mountain and the desert. There is a gulf that yawns between those who love Him and those who hate Him, between those who believe and those who do not believe. But when the years have bridged that gulf you shall know that He who lived in us is deathless, that He was the Son of God even as we are the children of God; that He was born of a virgin even as we are born of the husbandless earth.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000389","text":"Master, master singer, Master of words unspoken, Seven times was I born, and seven times have I died Since your last hasty visit and our brief welcome. And behold I live again, Remembering a day and a night among the hills, When your tide lifted us up.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000390","text":"Men would bless you or curse you; The curse, a protest against failure, The blessing, a hymn of the hunter Who comes back from the hills With provision for his mate.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000391","text":"You laughed for the marrow in their bones that was not yet ready for laughter; And you wept for their eyes that yet were dry. Your voice fathered their thoughts and their understanding. Your voice mothered their words and their breath.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000392","text":"Master, Master of Light, Whose eye dwells in the seeking fingers of the blind, You are still despised and mocked, A man too weak and infirm to be God, A God too much man to call forth adoration.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000393","text":"But Master, Sky-heart, Knight of our fairer dream, You do still tread this day; Nor bows nor spears shall stay your steps. You walk through all our arrows.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000394","text":"Poet, Singer, Great Heart, May our God bless your name, And the womb that held you, and the breasts that gave you milk. And may God forgive us all.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000395","text":"Life without Liberty is like a body without spirit. Liberty without thought is like a disturbed spirit … Life, liberty, and thought — three persons in one substance, eternal, never-ending, and unceasing.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000396","text":"Love and what generates it. Rebellion and what creates it. Liberty and what nourishes it. Three manifestations of God. And God is the conscience of the rational world.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000397","text":"How amazing time is, and how amazing we are. Time has been transformed, and we have changed; it has advanced and set us in motion; it has unveiled its face, inspiring us with bewilderment and exhilaration. Yesterday we complained of time and feared it, but today we love and embrace it. Indeed, we have begun to perceive its purposes and characteristics, and to comprehend its secrets and enigmas.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000398","text":"Yesterday we obeyed kings and bent our necks before emperors. But today we kneel only to truth, follow only beauty, and obey only love.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000399","text":"All that you see was and is for your sake. The numerous books, uncanny markings, and beautiful thoughts are the ghosts of souls who preceded you. The speech they weave is a link between you and your human siblings. The consequences that cause sorrow and rapture are the seeds that the past has sown in the field of the soul, and by which the future shall profit.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000400","text":"My Soul gave me good counsel, teaching me to love what the people abhor and to show good will toward the one they hate. It showed me that Love is a property not of the lover but of the beloved. Before my Soul taught me, Love was for me a delicate thread stretched between two adjacent pegs, but now it has been transformed into a halo; its first is its last, and its last is its first. It encompasses every being, slowly expanding to embrace all that ever will be.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000401","text":"My yearning is my cup, my burning thirst is my drink, and my solitude is my intoxication; I do not and shall not quench my thirst. But in this burning that is never extinguished is a joy that never wanes.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000402","text":"My Soul gave me good counsel, teaching me to touch what has never taken corporeal form or crystallized. It made me understand that touching something is half the task of comprehending it, and that what we grasp therein is part of what we desire from it.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000403","text":"My Soul gave me good counsel, teaching me never to delight in praise or to be distressed by reproach. Before my Soul taught me, I doubted the value of my accomplishments until the passing days sent someone who would extol or disparage them. But now I know that trees blossom in the spring and give their fruits in the summer without any desire for accolades. And they scatter their leaves abroad in the fall and denude themselves in the winter without fear of reproof.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000404","text":"My Soul gave me good counsel, teaching me that the lamp which I carry does not belong to me, and the song that I sing was not generated from within me. Even if I walk with light, I am not the light; and if I am a taut-stringed lute, I am not the lute player.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000405","text":"My thought is a tender leaf that sways in every direction and finds pleasure in its swaying. Your thought is an ancient dogma that cannot change you nor can you change it. My thought is new, and it tests me and I test it morn and eve. You have your thought and I have mine.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000406","text":"Your thought describes laws, courts, judges, punishments. Mine explains that when man makes a law, he either violates it or obeys it. If there is a basic law, we are all one before it. He who disdains the mean is himself mean. He who vaunts his scorn of the sinful vaunts his disdain of all humanity.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000407","text":"Your thought advocates Judaism, Brahmanism, Buddhism, Christianity, and Islam. In my thought there is only one universal religion, whose varied paths are but the fingers of the loving hand of the Supreme Being. In your thought there are the rich, the poor, and the beggared. My thought holds that there are no riches but life; that we are all beggars, and no benefactor exists save life herself.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000408","text":"Out of suffering have emerged the strongest souls; the most massive characters are seared with scars.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000409","text":"And God said, Love your enemy, & I obeyed Him & loved myself.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000410","text":"Travel and tell no one. Have a true love story and tell no one. Live happily and tell no one. People ruin beautiful things.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000411","text":"For Khalil Gibran no single religious tradition revealed the whole truth about life so he wove together insights from Eastern Christianity, Islam, Buddhism, American Transcendentalism, and the folklore of his native Lebanon to create his own universal \"Anthem of Humanity\" … he attacks narrow-mindedness, clerical hypocrisy and political injustice, and issues a declaration of faith in life itself.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000412","text":"Kahlil Gibran Tribute Site","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"Kahlil Gibran","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true,"isAffirmation":false},{"id":"mindful-000413","text":"The Twelve Illustrations In This Volume Are Reproduced From Original Drawings By The Author","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000414","text":"“His power came from some great reservoir of spiritual life else it could not have been so universal and so potent, but the majesty and beauty of the language with which he clothed it were all his own?”","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000415","text":"The Madman. 1918 Twenty Drawings. 1919 The Forerunner. 1920 The Prophet. 1923 Sand and Foam. 1926 Jesus the Son of Man. 1928 The Forth Gods. 1931 The Wanderer. 1932 The Garden of the Prophet 1933 Prose Poems. 1934 Nymphs of the Valley. 1948","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000416","text":"Almustafa, the chosen and the beloved, who was a dawn unto his own day, had waited twelve years in the city of Orphalese for his ship that was to return and bear him back to the isle of his birth.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000417","text":"And in the twelfth year, on the seventh day of Ielool, the month of reaping, he climbed the hill without the city walls and looked seaward; and he beheld his ship coming with the mist.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000418","text":"Then the gates of his heart were flung open, and his joy flew far over the sea. And he closed his eyes and prayed in the silences of his soul.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000419","text":"But as he descended the hill, a sadness came upon him, and he thought in his heart:","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000420","text":"How shall I go in peace and without sorrow? Nay, not without a wound in the spirit shall I leave this city.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000421","text":"Long were the days of pain I have spent within its walls, and long were the nights of aloneness; and who can depart from his pain and his aloneness without regret?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000422","text":"Too many fragments of the spirit have I scattered in these streets, and too many are the children of my longing that walk naked among these hills, and I cannot withdraw from them without a burden and an ache.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000423","text":"It is not a garment I cast off this day, but a skin that I tear with my own hands.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000424","text":"Nor is it a thought I leave behind me, but a heart made sweet with hunger and with thirst.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000425","text":"The sea that calls all things unto her calls me, and I must embark.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000426","text":"For to stay, though the hours burn in the night, is to freeze and crystallize and be bound in a mould.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000427","text":"Fain would I take with me all that is here. But how shall I?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000428","text":"A voice cannot carry the tongue and the lips that gave it wings. Alone must it seek the ether.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000429","text":"And alone and without his nest shall the eagle fly across the sun.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000430","text":"Now when he reached the foot of the hill, he turned again towards the sea, and he saw his ship approaching the harbour, and upon her prow the mariners, the men of his own land.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000431","text":"And his soul cried out to them, and he said:","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000432","text":"Sons of my ancient mother, you riders of the tides,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000433","text":"How often have you sailed in my dreams. And now you come in my awakening, which is my deeper dream.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000434","text":"Ready am I to go, and my eagerness with sails full set awaits the wind.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000435","text":"Only another breath will I breathe in this still air, only another loving look cast backward,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000436","text":"And then I shall stand among you, a seafarer among seafarers.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000437","text":"And you, vast sea, sleepless mother,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000438","text":"Who alone are peace and freedom to the river and the stream,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000439","text":"Only another winding will this stream make, only another murmur in this glade,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000440","text":"And then shall I come to you, a boundless drop to a boundless ocean.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000441","text":"And as he walked he saw from afar men and women leaving their fields and their vineyards and hastening towards the city gates.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000442","text":"And he heard their voices calling his name, and shouting from field to field telling one another of the coming of his ship.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000443","text":"Shall the day of parting be the day of gathering?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000444","text":"And shall it be said that my eve was in truth my dawn?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000445","text":"And what shall I give unto him who has left his plough in midfurrow, or to him who has stopped the wheel of his winepress?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000446","text":"Shall my heart become a tree heavy-laden with fruit that I may gather and give unto them?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000447","text":"And shall my desires flow like a fountain that I may fill their cups?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000448","text":"Am I a harp that the hand of the mighty may touch me, or a flute that his breath may pass through me?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000449","text":"A seeker of silences am I, and what treasure have I found in silences that I may dispense with confidence?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000450","text":"If this is my day of harvest, in what fields have I sowed the seed, and in what unremembered seasons?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000451","text":"If this indeed be the hour in which I lift up my lantern, it is not my flame that shall burn therein.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000452","text":"Empty and dark shall I raise my lantern,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000453","text":"And the guardian of the night shall fill it with oil and he shall light it also.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000454","text":"These things he said in words. But much in his heart remained unsaid. For he himself could not speak his deeper secret.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000455","text":"And when he entered into the city all the people came to meet him, and they were crying out to him as with one voice.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000456","text":"And the elders of the city stood forth and said:","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000457","text":"A noontide have you been in our twilight, and your youth has given us dreams to dream.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000458","text":"No stranger are you among us, nor a guest, but our son and our dearly beloved.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000459","text":"Suffer not yet our eyes to hunger for your face.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000460","text":"And the priests and the priestesses said unto him:","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000461","text":"Let not the waves of the sea separate us now, and the years you have spent in our midst become a memory.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000462","text":"You have walked among us a spirit, and your shadow has been a light upon our faces.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000463","text":"Much have we loved you. But speechless was our love, and with veils has it been veiled.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000464","text":"Yet now it cries aloud unto you, and would stand revealed before you.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000465","text":"And ever has it been that love knows not its own depth until the hour of separation.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000466","text":"And others came also and entreated him. But he answered them not. He only bent his head; and those who stood near saw his tears falling upon his breast.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000467","text":"And he and the people proceeded towards the great square before the temple.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000468","text":"And there came out of the sanctuary a woman whose name was Almitra. And she was a seeress.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000469","text":"And he looked upon her with exceeding tenderness, for it was she who had first sought and believed in him when he had been but a day in their city.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000470","text":"Prophet of God, in quest of the uttermost, long have you searched the distances for your ship.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000471","text":"And now your ship has come, and you must needs go.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000472","text":"Deep is your longing for the land of your memories and the dwelling place of your greater desires; and our love would not bind you nor our needs hold you.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000473","text":"Yet this we ask ere you leave us, that you speak to us and give us of your truth.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000474","text":"And we will give it unto our children, and they unto their children, and it shall not perish.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000475","text":"In your aloneness you have watched with our days, and in your wakefulness you have listened to the weeping and the laughter of our sleep.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000476","text":"Now therefore disclose us to ourselves, and tell us all that has been shown you of that which is between birth and death.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000477","text":"People of Orphalese, of what can I speak save of that which is even now moving within your souls?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000478","text":"Then said Almitra, Speak to us of _Love_.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000479","text":"And he raised his head and looked upon the people, and there fell a stillness upon them. And with a great voice he said:","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000480","text":"When love beckons to you, follow him,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000481","text":"Though his ways are hard and steep.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000482","text":"And when his wings enfold you yield to him,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000483","text":"Though the sword hidden among his pinions may wound you.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000484","text":"And when he speaks to you believe in him,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000485","text":"Though his voice may shatter your dreams as the north wind lays waste the garden.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000486","text":"For even as love crowns you so shall he crucify you. Even as he is for your growth so is he for your pruning.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000487","text":"Even as he ascends to your height and caresses your tenderest branches that quiver in the sun,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000488","text":"So shall he descend to your roots and shake them in their clinging to the earth.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000489","text":"Like sheaves of corn he gathers you unto himself.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000490","text":"He threshes you to make you naked.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000491","text":"He sifts you to free you from your husks.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000492","text":"He kneads you until you are pliant;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000493","text":"And then he assigns you to his sacred fire, that you may become sacred bread for God’s sacred feast.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000494","text":"All these things shall love do unto you that you may know the secrets of your heart, and in that knowledge become a fragment of Life’s heart.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000495","text":"But if in your fear you would seek only love’s peace and love’s pleasure,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000496","text":"Then it is better for you that you cover your nakedness and pass out of love’s threshing-floor,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000497","text":"Into the seasonless world where you shall laugh, but not all of your laughter, and weep, but not all of your tears.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000498","text":"Love gives naught but itself and takes naught but from itself.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000499","text":"Love possesses not nor would it be possessed;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000500","text":"For love is sufficient unto love.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000501","text":"When you love you should not say, “God is in my heart,” but rather, “I am in the heart of God.”","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000502","text":"And think not you can direct the course of love, for love, if it finds you worthy, directs your course.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000503","text":"Love has no other desire but to fulfil itself.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000504","text":"But if you love and must needs have desires, let these be your desires:","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000505","text":"To melt and be like a running brook that sings its melody to the night.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000506","text":"To know the pain of too much tenderness.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000507","text":"To be wounded by your own understanding of love;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000508","text":"And to bleed willingly and joyfully.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000509","text":"To wake at dawn with a winged heart and give thanks for another day of loving;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000510","text":"To rest at the noon hour and meditate love’s ecstacy;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000511","text":"To return home at eventide with gratitude;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000512","text":"And then to sleep with a prayer for the beloved in your heart and a song of praise upon your lips.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000513","text":"Then Almitra spoke again and said, And what of _Marriage_ master?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000514","text":"You were born together, and together you shall be forevermore.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000515","text":"You shall be together when the white wings of death scatter your days.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000516","text":"Aye, you shall be together even in the silent memory of God.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000517","text":"But let there be spaces in your togetherness,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000518","text":"And let the winds of the heavens dance between you.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000519","text":"Love one another, but make not a bond of love:","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000520","text":"Let it rather be a moving sea between the shores of your souls.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000521","text":"Fill each other’s cup but drink not from one cup.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000522","text":"Give one another of your bread but eat not from the same loaf.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000523","text":"Sing and dance together and be joyous, but let each one of you be alone,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000524","text":"Even as the strings of a lute are alone though they quiver with the same music.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000525","text":"Give your hearts, but not into each other’s keeping.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000526","text":"For only the hand of Life can contain your hearts.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000527","text":"And stand together yet not too near together:","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000528","text":"For the pillars of the temple stand apart,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000529","text":"And the oak tree and the cypress grow not in each other’s shadow.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000530","text":"And a woman who held a babe against her bosom said, Speak to us of _Children_.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000531","text":"Your children are not your children.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000532","text":"They are the sons and daughters of Life’s longing for itself.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000533","text":"They come through you but not from you,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000534","text":"And though they are with you yet they belong not to you.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000535","text":"You may give them your love but not your thoughts,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000536","text":"For they have their own thoughts.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000537","text":"You may house their bodies but not their souls,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000538","text":"For their souls dwell in the house of tomorrow, which you cannot visit, not even in your dreams.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000539","text":"You may strive to be like them, but seek not to make them like you.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000540","text":"For life goes not backward nor tarries with yesterday.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000541","text":"You are the bows from which your children as living arrows are sent forth.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000542","text":"The archer sees the mark upon the path of the infinite, and He bends you with His might that His arrows may go swift and far.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000543","text":"Let your bending in the Archer’s hand be for gladness;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000544","text":"For even as he loves the arrow that flies, so He loves also the bow that is stable.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000545","text":"Then said a rich man, Speak to us of _Giving_.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000546","text":"You give but little when you give of your possessions.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000547","text":"It is when you give of yourself that you truly give.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000548","text":"For what are your possessions but things you keep and guard for fear you may need them tomorrow?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000549","text":"And tomorrow, what shall tomorrow bring to the overprudent dog burying bones in the trackless sand as he follows the pilgrims to the holy city?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000550","text":"And what is fear of need but need itself?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000551","text":"Is not dread of thirst when your well is full, the thirst that is unquenchable?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000552","text":"There are those who give little of the much which they have--and they give it for recognition and their hidden desire makes their gifts unwholesome.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000553","text":"And there are those who have little and give it all.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000554","text":"These are the believers in life and the bounty of life, and their coffer is never empty.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000555","text":"There are those who give with joy, and that joy is their reward.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000556","text":"And there are those who give with pain, and that pain is their baptism.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000557","text":"And there are those who give and know not pain in giving, nor do they seek joy, nor give with mindfulness of virtue;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000558","text":"They give as in yonder valley the myrtle breathes its fragrance into space.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000559","text":"Through the hands of such as these God speaks, and from behind their eyes He smiles upon the earth.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000560","text":"It is well to give when asked, but it is better to give unasked, through understanding;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000561","text":"And to the open-handed the search for one who shall receive is joy greater than giving.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000562","text":"And is there aught you would withhold?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000563","text":"All you have shall some day be given;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000564","text":"Therefore give now, that the season of giving may be yours and not your inheritors’.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000565","text":"You often say, “I would give, but only to the deserving.”","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000566","text":"The trees in your orchard say not so, nor the flocks in your pasture.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000567","text":"They give that they may live, for to withhold is to perish.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000568","text":"Surely he who is worthy to receive his days and his nights, is worthy of all else from you.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000569","text":"And he who has deserved to drink from the ocean of life deserves to fill his cup from your little stream.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000570","text":"And what desert greater shall there be, than that which lies in the courage and the confidence, nay the charity, of receiving?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000571","text":"And who are you that men should rend their bosom and unveil their pride, that you may see their worth naked and their pride unabashed?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000572","text":"See first that you yourself deserve to be a giver, and an instrument of giving.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000573","text":"For in truth it is life that gives unto life--while you, who deem yourself a giver, are but a witness.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000574","text":"And you receivers--and you are all receivers--assume no weight of gratitude, lest you lay a yoke upon yourself and upon him who gives.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000575","text":"Rather rise together with the giver on his gifts as on wings;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000576","text":"For to be overmindful of your debt, is to doubt his generosity who has the freehearted earth for mother, and God for father.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000577","text":"Then an old man, a keeper of an inn, said, Speak to us of _Eating and Drinking_.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000578","text":"Would that you could live on the fragrance of the earth, and like an air plant be sustained by the light.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000579","text":"But since you must kill to eat, and rob the newly born of its mother’s milk to quench your thirst, let it then be an act of worship,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000580","text":"And let your board stand an altar on which the pure and the innocent of forest and plain are sacrificed for that which is purer and still more innocent in man.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000581","text":"When you kill a beast say to him in your heart,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000582","text":"“By the same power that slays you, I too am slain; and I too shall be consumed.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000583","text":"For the law that delivered you into my hand shall deliver me into a mightier hand.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000584","text":"Your blood and my blood is naught but the sap that feeds the tree of heaven.”","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000585","text":"And when you crush an apple with your teeth, say to it in your heart,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000586","text":"“Your seeds shall live in my body,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000587","text":"And the buds of your tomorrow shall blossom in my heart,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000588","text":"And your fragrance shall be my breath, And together we shall rejoice through all the seasons.”","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000589","text":"And in the autumn, when you gather the grapes of your vineyards for the winepress, say in your heart,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000590","text":"“I too am a vineyard, and my fruit shall be gathered for the winepress,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000591","text":"And like new wine I shall be kept in eternal vessels.”","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000592","text":"And in winter, when you draw the wine, let there be in your heart a song for each cup;","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000593","text":"And let there be in the song a remembrance for the autumn days, and for the vineyard, and for the winepress.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000594","text":"Then a ploughman said, Speak to us of _Work_.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000595","text":"You work that you may keep pace with the earth and the soul of the earth.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000596","text":"For to be idle is to become a stranger unto the seasons, and to step out of life’s procession, that marches in majesty and proud submission towards the infinite.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000597","text":"When you work you are a flute through whose heart the whispering of the hours turns to music.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000598","text":"Which of you would be a reed, dumb and silent, when all else sings together in unison?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000599","text":"Always you have been told that work is a curse and labour a misfortune.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"mindful-000600","text":"But I say to you that when you work you fulfil a part of earth’s furthest dream, assigned to you when that dream was born,","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet (1923)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,presence","theme:presence","tradition:buddhism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"isAffirmation":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"}]}